---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site } from '../content/site';
---
<BaseLayout title="Open source — Koru" description="Koru is open source under Apache-2.0, with public governance, contribution, security, and attribution documents." canonicalPath="/open-source/">
  <header class="page-hero text-shell"><p class="eyebrow">Open source</p><h1>Inspect the decisions that handle private writing.</h1><p class="lede">Koru is licensed under Apache-2.0. The repository publishes its product and security contract before asking anyone to trust a binary.</p></header>
  <article class="prose text-shell">
    <div class="actions"><a class="button button-primary" href={site.repository}>View builderking/koru</a><a class="button button-secondary" href={site.contributing}>Contribution guide</a><a class="button button-secondary" href={site.license}>Apache-2.0 license</a></div>
    <h2>Attribution</h2>
    <p>Koru is copyright 2026 BuilderKing contributors. It includes software developed by the Koru open-source community. Third-party attribution notices will be audited and added to the repository's NOTICE and release materials before the first distributed binary.</p>
    <h2>Governance</h2>
    <p>The repository includes a governance model, code of conduct, contribution guide, support policy, and private security-reporting route. Locked behavior—especially fresh-input eligibility, explicit insertion, <code>clp</code>, and privacy defaults—requires an explicit decision record to change.</p>
    <h2>Contribute safely</h2>
    <p>Use synthetic test content. Never paste real prompts, clipboard history, credentials, client information, vault databases, Keychain exports, or other private writing into public issues, discussions, tests, screenshots, or diagnostics.</p>
    <h2>Brand status</h2>
    <p>Koru is a working product name. Trademark and appropriate Māori cultural review are still required before an irreversible logo system or public brand launch. This website therefore uses a plain wordmark and neutral letter glyph rather than a koru spiral or Māori-derived visual language.</p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
